INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (59,1,'2023-05-10 17:37:56','2023-05-10 17:37:56','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":60,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/galaxy1-1024x680.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-60\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. The Milky Way: Unveiling the Secrets of Our Galactic Home</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our home, the Milky Way, is a barred spiral galaxy. It is estimated to contain between 100 to 400 billion stars, including our own Sun. The Milky Way is shaped like a flat disk with a central bulge and spiral arms extending outward.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Andromeda Galaxy: A Celestial Neighbor on a Collision Course</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Andromeda Galaxy, also known as M31, is the closest spiral galaxy to the Milky Way. It is approximately 2.5 million light-years away from us. Andromeda and the Milky Way are on a collision course and are expected to merge in about 4 billion years, forming a new galaxy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":61,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/galaxy-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-61\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Elliptical Galaxies: Mysterious Spheres of Time and Space</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Elliptical galaxies are the most common type of galaxy in the universe. Unlike spiral galaxies, they lack distinct spiral arms and are often shaped like ellipsoids or spheres. Elliptical galaxies are typically older and contain older stars.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Active Galactic Nuclei: Illuminating the Universe\'s Powerhouses</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some galaxies have an extremely bright and energetic core known as an active galactic nucleus (AGN). AGNs are powered by supermassive black holes at the centers of galaxies, which accrete matter and release tremendous amounts of energy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":62,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/galaxy2-1024x685.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-62\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Dwarf Galaxies: Small Yet Significant Pieces of Cosmic Puzzle</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dwarf galaxies are smaller and less massive compared to their larger counterparts. They are abundant in the universe and often orbit around larger galaxies like the Milky Way. Despite their size, dwarf galaxies can still host active star formation and contribute to the evolution of the universe.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Breathtaking Facts About Galaxies','Galaxies','publish','open','open','','galaxies','','','2023-05-16 21:02:29','2023-05-16 21:02:29','',0,'http://unifacts.local/?p=59',0,'post','',0);
