INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (96,1,'2023-05-16 20:53:26','2023-05-16 20:53:26','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":65,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/universe2-1024x736.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-65\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.</strong> <strong>The universe is expanding!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The universe is constantly expanding. Scientists have observed that galaxies are moving away from each other, indicating that the universe is expanding. This discovery led to the Big Bang theory, which suggests that the universe originated from a hot, dense state and has been expanding ever since.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. There are giant vacuum cleaners in space!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Black holes are regions in space where gravity is so strong that nothing, not even light, can escape from them. They form when massive stars collapse under their own gravity. Black holes have a powerful gravitational pull that can distort space and time, making them fascinating objects to study.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":66,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/universe1-1024x640.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-66\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. The universe is dark, but not empty!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The majority of the universe is composed of dark matter and dark energy, yet they remain mysterious. Dark matter does not interact with light and other forms of electromagnetic radiation, but its gravitational effects can be observed. Dark energy, on the other hand, is believed to be responsible for the accelerating expansion of the universe.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Microwaves in space?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The cosmic microwave background (CMB) radiation is a faint glow of electromagnetic radiation that permeates the entire universe. It is considered to be the remnant heat from the Big Bang. By studying the CMB, scientists gain valuable insights into the early stages of the universe and its evolution.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":67,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/blackHole-1024x461.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-67\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Exoplanets</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Exoplanets are planets that exist outside our solar system. The discovery of exoplanets has revolutionized our understanding of the universe and the possibility of other habitable worlds. Scientists have identified thousands of exoplanets, some of which may have conditions suitable for life as we know it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Amazing Facts About the Universe','The Universe','inherit','closed','closed','','64-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 20:53:26','2023-05-16 20:53:26','',64,'https://unifacts.local/?p=96',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (98,1,'2023-05-16 20:56:51','2023-05-16 20:56:51','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":60,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/galaxy1-1024x680.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-60\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. The Milky Way</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our home, the Milky Way, is a barred spiral galaxy. It is estimated to contain between 100 to 400 billion stars, including our own Sun. The Milky Way is shaped like a flat disk with a central bulge and spiral arms extending outward.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Out closest neighbour</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Andromeda Galaxy, also known as M31, is the closest spiral galaxy to the Milky Way. It is approximately 2.5 million light-years away from us. Andromeda and the Milky Way are on a collision course and are expected to merge in about 4 billion years, forming a new galaxy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":61,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/galaxy-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-61\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Elliptical Galaxies</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Elliptical galaxies are the most common type of galaxy in the universe. Unlike spiral galaxies, they lack distinct spiral arms and are often shaped like ellipsoids or spheres. Elliptical galaxies are typically older and contain older stars.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Active Galactic Nuclei (AGN)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some galaxies have an extremely bright and energetic core known as an active galactic nucleus (AGN). AGNs are powered by supermassive black holes at the centers of galaxies, which accrete matter and release tremendous amounts of energy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":62,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/galaxy2-1024x685.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-62\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Dwarf Galaxies</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dwarf galaxies are smaller and less massive compared to their larger counterparts. They are abundant in the universe and often orbit around larger galaxies like the Milky Way. Despite their size, dwarf galaxies can still host active star formation and contribute to the evolution of the universe.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Breathtaking Facts About Galaxies','Galaxies','inherit','closed','closed','','59-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 20:56:51','2023-05-16 20:56:51','',59,'https://unifacts.local/?p=98',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (100,1,'2023-05-16 20:59:33','2023-05-16 20:59:33','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":55,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/neptune-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-55\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Eighth planet from the Sun</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Neptune is the eighth planet from the Sun in our solar system. It is located about 4.5 billion kilometers (2.8 billion miles) away from the Sun. Due to its distant location, Neptune experiences extremely cold temperatures and takes about 165 Earth years to complete one orbit around the Sun.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Beautiful blue color</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the most distinctive features of Neptune is its vibrant blue color. The planet\'s atmosphere contains a high concentration of methane gas, which absorbs red light and reflects blue light, giving Neptune its striking blue hue.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":56,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/neptune2-1024x895.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-56\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Stormy weather</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Neptune is known for its active and turbulent weather patterns. It exhibits powerful winds, with the fastest recorded winds in the solar system, reaching speeds of over 2,100 kilometers per hour (1,300 miles per hour). The most famous storm on Neptune is the Great Dark Spot, a massive storm system similar to Jupiter\'s Great Red Spot.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Rings and moons</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Like other gas giants, Neptune has a system of rings and a collection of moons. Its rings are faint and composed of dust particles and ice chunks. Neptune has 14 known moons, with Triton being the largest and most interesting. Triton is unique because it orbits Neptune in the opposite direction of the planet\'s rotation, suggesting that it may have been captured by Neptune\'s gravity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":57,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/neptune1-1024x942.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-57\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Icy giant</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Neptune is classified as an ice giant due to its composition. It has a relatively small rocky core surrounded by a thick mantle of water, ammonia, and methane ices. The atmosphere is primarily composed of hydrogen and helium, with traces of methane giving it its blue color.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Stunning Facts About Neptune','Neptune','inherit','closed','closed','','54-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 20:59:33','2023-05-16 20:59:33','',54,'https://unifacts.local/?p=100',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (101,1,'2023-05-16 21:02:28','2023-05-16 21:02:28','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":60,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/galaxy1-1024x680.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-60\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. The Milky Way: Unveiling the Secrets of Our Galactic Home</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our home, the Milky Way, is a barred spiral galaxy. It is estimated to contain between 100 to 400 billion stars, including our own Sun. The Milky Way is shaped like a flat disk with a central bulge and spiral arms extending outward.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Andromeda Galaxy: A Celestial Neighbor on a Collision Course</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Andromeda Galaxy, also known as M31, is the closest spiral galaxy to the Milky Way. It is approximately 2.5 million light-years away from us. Andromeda and the Milky Way are on a collision course and are expected to merge in about 4 billion years, forming a new galaxy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":61,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/galaxy-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-61\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Elliptical Galaxies: Mysterious Spheres of Time and Space</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Elliptical galaxies are the most common type of galaxy in the universe. Unlike spiral galaxies, they lack distinct spiral arms and are often shaped like ellipsoids or spheres. Elliptical galaxies are typically older and contain older stars.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Active Galactic Nuclei: Illuminating the Universe\'s Powerhouses</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some galaxies have an extremely bright and energetic core known as an active galactic nucleus (AGN). AGNs are powered by supermassive black holes at the centers of galaxies, which accrete matter and release tremendous amounts of energy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":62,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/galaxy2-1024x685.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-62\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Dwarf Galaxies: Small Yet Significant Pieces of Cosmic Puzzle</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dwarf galaxies are smaller and less massive compared to their larger counterparts. They are abundant in the universe and often orbit around larger galaxies like the Milky Way. Despite their size, dwarf galaxies can still host active star formation and contribute to the evolution of the universe.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Breathtaking Facts About Galaxies','Galaxies','inherit','closed','closed','','59-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:02:28','2023-05-16 21:02:28','',59,'https://unifacts.local/?p=101',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (102,1,'2023-05-16 21:04:24','2023-05-16 21:04:24','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":65,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/universe2-1024x736.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-65\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Expanding Universe: Unveiling the Unstoppable Stretch of Space</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The universe is constantly expanding. Scientists have observed that galaxies are moving away from each other, indicating that the universe is expanding. This discovery led to the Big Bang theory, which suggests that the universe originated from a hot, dense state and has been expanding ever since.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Black Holes: The Enigmatic Vortexes of Cosmic Conundrums</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Black holes are regions in space where gravity is so strong that nothing, not even light, can escape from them. They form when massive stars collapse under their own gravity. Black holes have a powerful gravitational pull that can distort space and time, making them fascinating objects to study.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":66,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/universe1-1024x640.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-66\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Dark Matter and Dark Energy: Unveiling the Veiled Forces of the Universe</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The majority of the universe is composed of dark matter and dark energy, yet they remain mysterious. Dark matter does not interact with light and other forms of electromagnetic radiation, but its gravitational effects can be observed. Dark energy, on the other hand, is believed to be responsible for the accelerating expansion of the universe.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Cosmic Microwave Background Radiation: The Echoes of Creation\'s Birth</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The cosmic microwave background (CMB) radiation is a faint glow of electromagnetic radiation that permeates the entire universe. It is considered to be the remnant heat from the Big Bang. By studying the CMB, scientists gain valuable insights into the early stages of the universe and its evolution.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":67,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/blackHole-1024x461.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-67\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Exoplanets: Peering Beyond Our Solar System\'s Boundaries</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Exoplanets are planets that exist outside our solar system. The discovery of exoplanets has revolutionized our understanding of the universe and the possibility of other habitable worlds. Scientists have identified thousands of exoplanets, some of which may have conditions suitable for life as we know it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Amazing Facts About the Universe','The Universe','inherit','closed','closed','','64-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:04:24','2023-05-16 21:04:24','',64,'https://unifacts.local/?p=102',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (103,1,'2023-05-16 21:06:25','2023-05-16 21:06:25','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":55,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/neptune-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-55\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Eighth Planet from the Sun: Neptune - The Distant Wonder of our Solar System!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Neptune is the eighth planet from the Sun in our solar system. It is located about 4.5 billion kilometers (2.8 billion miles) away from the Sun. Due to its distant location, Neptune experiences extremely cold temperatures and takes about 165 Earth years to complete one orbit around the Sun.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Beautiful Blue Color: Neptune - Painting the Universe Blue with Its Enigmatic Hue!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the most distinctive features of Neptune is its vibrant blue color. The planet\'s atmosphere contains a high concentration of methane gas, which absorbs red light and reflects blue light, giving Neptune its striking blue hue.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":56,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/neptune2-1024x895.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-56\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Stormy Weather: Neptune - Unleashing the Fury of Winds in the Deep Cosmic Seas!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Neptune is known for its active and turbulent weather patterns. It exhibits powerful winds, with the fastest recorded winds in the solar system, reaching speeds of over 2,100 kilometers per hour (1,300 miles per hour). The most famous storm on Neptune is the Great Dark Spot, a massive storm system similar to Jupiter\'s Great Red Spot.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Rings and Moons: Neptune - A Celestial Symphony of Rings and Moons in Harmonious Dance!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Like other gas giants, Neptune has a system of rings and a collection of moons. Its rings are faint and composed of dust particles and ice chunks. Neptune has 14 known moons, with Triton being the largest and most interesting. Triton is unique because it orbits Neptune in the opposite direction of the planet\'s rotation, suggesting that it may have been captured by Neptune\'s gravity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":57,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/neptune1-1024x942.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-57\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Icy Giant: Neptune - Unlocking the Secrets of the Chilled and Mystical Realm!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Neptune is classified as an ice giant due to its composition. It has a relatively small rocky core surrounded by a thick mantle of water, ammonia, and methane ices. The atmosphere is primarily composed of hydrogen and helium, with traces of methane giving it its blue color.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Stunning Facts About Neptune','Neptune','inherit','closed','closed','','54-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:06:25','2023-05-16 21:06:25','',54,'https://unifacts.local/?p=103',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (105,1,'2023-05-16 21:10:36','2023-05-16 21:10:36','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":80,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/uranus2-2-1024x717.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-80\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Tilted on its Side: Uranus - The Sideways Wonder of the Solar System!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Uranus has a unique feature—it rotates on its side with an extreme tilt of about 98 degrees, making it appear as if it\'s rolling along its orbit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Mysterious Blue-Green Atmosphere: Uranus - The Enigmatic Jewel of Aquamarine Skies!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Uranus has a striking blue-green color due to its atmosphere containing high concentrations of methane gas, which absorbs red light and reflects blue-green light.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":50,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/uranus-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-50\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Icy, Gaseous Giant: Uranus - Unlocking the Secrets of the Frigid Gas Giant!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Uranus is classified as an ice giant, with a composition of mainly hydrogen and helium gases, along with icy elements like water, methane, and ammonia.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Moons Galore: Uranus - A Moon Wonderland in Orbit around the Seventh Planet!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Uranus has 27 known moons, with some of the most notable ones being Miranda, Ariel, Umbriel, Titania, and Oberon, each with its own unique characteristics.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":49,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/uranus1-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-49\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Diamond Rain: Uranus - Where Diamonds Fall from the Sky!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Scientists believe that within the atmosphere of Uranus, intense pressure and temperature conditions can create diamond rain, where carbon-rich compounds form and fall towards the planet\'s core.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Spectacular Facts About Uranus','Uranus','inherit','closed','closed','','48-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:10:36','2023-05-16 21:10:36','',48,'https://unifacts.local/?p=105',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (107,1,'2023-05-16 21:12:49','2023-05-16 21:12:49','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":44,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/saturn2-1024x549.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-44\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Spectacular Ring System: Saturn - The Ringed Marvel of the Solar System!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Saturn is renowned for its iconic ring system, consisting of multiple rings made up of ice particles, dust, and rocks. These rings are a sight to behold and make Saturn truly unique.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Massive and Majestic: Saturn - The Grand Giant Among Planets!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Saturn is the second-largest planet in our solar system, boasting a diameter of about 120,500 kilometers (74,900 miles). Its immense size and impressive presence make it a true celestial behemoth.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":45,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/saturn-1024x888.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-45\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Many Moons to Explore: Saturn - A Moon Haven in the Saturnian Realm!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Saturn has an extensive moon system, with over 80 confirmed moons, including notable ones like Titan, Enceladus, and Mimas. These diverse moons offer intriguing possibilities for exploration and discovery.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Hexagonal Storm: Saturn - Where a Mysterious Hexagon Rages On!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Saturn\'s north pole features a mesmerizing hexagonal-shaped storm, known as the \"Saturnian hexagon.\" This unusual atmospheric phenomenon continues to captivate scientists, leaving them puzzled.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":46,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/saturn1-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-46\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Light as a Feather: Saturn - The Lightest Planet in the Solar System!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite its enormous size, Saturn has a relatively low density, making it less dense than water. If you could find a bathtub big enough, Saturn would float!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Unbelievable Facts About Saturn','Saturn','inherit','closed','closed','','43-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:12:49','2023-05-16 21:12:49','',43,'https://unifacts.local/?p=107',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (109,1,'2023-05-16 21:22:43','2023-05-16 21:22:43','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":39,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/jupiter-1024x585.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-39\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. King of the Planets: Jupiter - The Majestic Monarch of the Solar System!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jupiter is the largest planet in our solar system, dominating the celestial stage with its immense size and captivating presence. Its colossal stature sets it apart as the king of all planets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Stormy Swirls: Jupiter - Unleashing the Ferocious Fury of the Great Red Spot!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jupiter boasts a colossal storm known as the Great Red Spot, a swirling tempest that has been raging for centuries. This enigmatic storm is larger than Earth and a captivating feature of Jupiter\'s atmosphere.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":40,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/jupiter1-1024x878.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-40\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Moon Dance: Jupiter - A Magnificent Moonscape of Wonders!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jupiter hosts a vast family of moons, with a total of 79 known moons. Among them, Ganymede, the largest moon in the solar system, and Io, the most volcanically active moon, showcase the captivating lunar dance around Jupiter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Gas Giant: Jupiter - A Gaseous Wonderland of Mystery and Intrigue!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jupiter is classified as a gas giant, consisting primarily of hydrogen and helium. Its thick atmosphere hides a turbulent and dynamic world, making it a fascinating realm for scientific exploration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":41,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/jupiter2-1024x647.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-41\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Protective Shield: Jupiter - The Mighty Guardian Shielding the Inner Solar System!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jupiter\'s immense gravitational pull acts as a cosmic shield, attracting and deflecting potential threats like asteroids and comets away from the inner solar system. Its protective role makes Jupiter a crucial guardian of our celestial neighborhood.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Freaky Facts About Jupiter','Jupiter','inherit','closed','closed','','38-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:22:43','2023-05-16 21:22:43','',38,'https://unifacts.local/?p=109',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (111,1,'2023-05-16 21:24:28','2023-05-16 21:24:28','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":34,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/mars-1024x576.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-34\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. The Red Planet: Mars - Unveiling the Mysteries of the Crimson World!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Mars is famously known as the \"Red Planet\" due to its rusty, reddish appearance. Its captivating crimson hue has intrigued astronomers and inspired countless imaginations, fueling the quest to uncover the secrets of this enigmatic world.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Martian Landmarks: Mars - The Grand Canyons and Volcanic Giants of Another World!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Mars boasts incredible geological features, including Valles Marineris, a system of canyons that stretches across its surface, and Olympus Mons, the largest volcano in the solar system. These colossal landmarks invite exploration and awe-inspiring discoveries.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":35,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/mars1-1024x954.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-35\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Ancient Martian Oceans: Mars - Traces of a Watery Past on the Deserted Planet!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Scientists believe that Mars once harbored vast oceans, evidenced by features such as dry riverbeds and ancient lake beds. Unraveling the mysteries of Mars\' watery past fuels the quest to understand its potential for supporting life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Dust Storms and Dust Devils: Mars - Unleashing the Fiery Fury of Martian Tempests!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Mars experiences intense dust storms that engulf its entire surface, obscuring visibility and reshaping the landscape. These tempests, along with the mesmerizing phenomena of dust devils, showcase the dynamic and ever-changing nature of Mars\' atmosphere.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":36,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/mars2-1024x1002.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-36\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Human Exploration Dreams: Mars - A Red Oasis Beckoning Humanity\'s Journey Beyond Earth!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Mars has captivated human imagination as a potential destination for human exploration and colonization. The dream of stepping foot on Mars ignites the spirit of adventure, pushing the boundaries of human achievement and paving the way for an interplanetary future.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Chilling Facts About Mars','Mars','inherit','closed','closed','','33-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:24:28','2023-05-16 21:24:28','',33,'https://unifacts.local/?p=111',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (113,1,'2023-05-16 21:26:19','2023-05-16 21:26:19','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":29,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/moon1-1024x986.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-29\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Earth\'s Celestial Companion: The Moon - Our Enigmatic Partner in the Night Sky!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Moon is Earth\'s only natural satellite, casting its gentle glow upon our planet and captivating our imaginations throughout history. Discover the fascinating mysteries and hidden tales of our enigmatic lunar companion.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Moon Phases: The Moon - A Cosmic Ballet of Waxing, Waning, and Mesmerizing Phases!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Moon undergoes a mesmerizing cycle of phases, transforming from a slender crescent to a full, radiant disc and back again. Unveil the celestial choreography behind the Moon\'s captivating dance of light and darkness.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":30,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/moon-1024x682.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-30\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Lunar Landings: The Moon - Humanity\'s Giant Leap onto the Lunar Surface!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Moon has been the stage for historic human achievements, including the Apollo lunar landings. Explore the triumphs, challenges, and extraordinary endeavors that led to mankind\'s unforgettable footprints on the lunar landscape.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Moonquakes and Lunar Tremors: The Moon - Unraveling the Rumbles beneath the Lunar Surface!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite its serene appearance, the Moon experiences moonquakes and tremors, offering glimpses into its geologic activity. Delve into the vibrations and mysteries that lie beneath the tranquil facade of Earth\'s celestial companion.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":31,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/moon2-1024x682.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-31\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Moon\'s Far Side: The Moon - Exploring the Hidden Face of our Mysterious Celestial Neighbor!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Moon\'s far side, forever hidden from Earth\'s view until space exploration, presents an intriguing and unexplored realm. Embark on a journey to unravel the mysteries and discover the untrodden territories of the enigmatic far side of the Moon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Scary Facts About the Moon','The Moon','inherit','closed','closed','','28-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:26:19','2023-05-16 21:26:19','',28,'https://unifacts.local/?p=113',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (115,1,'2023-05-16 21:28:03','2023-05-16 21:28:03','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":24,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/earth-999x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-24\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. The Blue Planet: Earth - A Shimmering Oasis of Life in the Vastness of Space!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Earth, with its abundant water and vibrant biosphere, stands out as a breathtaking oasis of life amidst the cosmic expanse. Uncover the secrets of our remarkable planet, its interconnected ecosystems, and the awe-inspiring diversity of life it nurtures.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Dynamic Tectonic Plates: Earth - Where Continents Collide and Mountains Rise!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Earth\'s surface is a patchwork of shifting tectonic plates, constantly rearranging and shaping our planet\'s topography. Journey into the depths of Earth\'s dynamic geological forces and witness the magnificent formation of mountains, valleys, and oceans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/earth1-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. The Water Planet: Earth - An Aqueous Wonderland Teeming with Marine Marvels!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With vast oceans covering approximately 70% of its surface, Earth is a water world like no other. Dive beneath the waves and explore the breathtaking marine ecosystems, home to captivating creatures, stunning coral reefs, and hidden wonders.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. The Breath of Life: Earth - A Precious Atmosphere Nurturing Living Beings!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Earth\'s atmosphere envelopes us with the gift of life, providing the perfect balance of gases and protecting us from the harshness of space. Embark on an atmospheric adventure and uncover the fascinating science behind our life-sustaining air.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":26,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/earth2-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-26\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Gaia\'s Biodiversity: Earth - A Tapestry of Life\'s Splendor, Unraveling Nature\'s Symphony!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Earth showcases an astonishing array of flora and fauna, from the tiniest microorganisms to majestic forests and awe-inspiring wildlife. Explore the rich tapestry of Earth\'s biodiversity, where countless species coexist, interact, and contribute to the intricate web of life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Weird Facts About the Earth','The Earth','inherit','closed','closed','','23-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:28:03','2023-05-16 21:28:03','',23,'https://unifacts.local/?p=115',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (117,1,'2023-05-16 21:29:53','2023-05-16 21:29:53','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":18,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/venus2-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-18\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Venus - The Fiery Jewel of the Sky: Unveiling the Mysteries of Earth\'s Scorching Sister!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Step into the scorching realm of Venus, Earth\'s blazing sister planet, and unravel the enigmatic secrets of its extreme surface temperature, thick atmosphere, and mesmerizing celestial beauty.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Runaway Greenhouse Effect: Venus - A Sweltering Inferno Trapped in a Blanket of Carbon Dioxide!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Witness the consequences of an out-of-control greenhouse effect on Venus, where a dense atmosphere shrouded in carbon dioxide traps heat, creating a runaway greenhouse effect and making it the hottest planet in our solar system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":19,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/venus1-1024x682.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-19\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Venusian Acid Rain: Exploring the Stormy Showers of Sulfuric Acid on Earth\'s Fiery Twin!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Delve into the hostile atmosphere of Venus, where sulfuric acid clouds swirl and raindrops of acid fall from the sky, painting a picture of an otherworldly and corrosive environment unlike anything found on Earth.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Retrograde Rotation: Venus - A Planet That Dances to Its Own Celestial Rhythm!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Discover the peculiar dance of Venus as it spins in the opposite direction of most other planets, with its retrograde rotation defying the conventions of our solar system and leaving astronomers intrigued by its celestial choreography.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":21,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/venus-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-21\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Venus - The Morning and Evening Star: Unveiling the Shimmering Beauty in the Skies!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Marvel at the radiant presence of Venus, often hailed as the \"Morning Star\" or the \"Evening Star,\" shining brilliantly in the sky and captivating stargazers throughout history with its celestial charm.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Incredible Facts About Venus','Venus','inherit','closed','closed','','17-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:29:53','2023-05-16 21:29:53','',17,'https://unifacts.local/?p=117',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (119,1,'2023-05-16 21:32:54','2023-05-16 21:32:54','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":13,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/mercury-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-13\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Mercury - The Swift Messenger: Racing Through the Solar System at Blistering Speeds!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Explore the captivating speed of Mercury, the fastest planet in our solar system, as it races through its orbit, completing a full revolution around the Sun in just 88 Earth days, defying the laws of cosmic velocity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Extreme Temperature Swings: Unveiling the Scorching Days and Freezing Nights on the Planet Closest to the Sun!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dive into the temperature extremes of Mercury, where daytime temperatures can soar to scorching highs of 800 degrees Fahrenheit (430 degrees Celsius), only to plummet to bone-chilling lows of -290 degrees Fahrenheit (-180 degrees Celsius) during its long, frigid nights.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":14,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/mercury1-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-14\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Giant Caloris Basin: Witnessing the Gigantic Impact Crater That Shaped Mercury\'s Landscape!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Embark on a journey to the colossal Caloris Basin, an impact crater on Mercury that stretches over 960 miles (1,550 kilometers) in diameter, revealing the dramatic forces of cosmic collisions that have shaped the planet\'s rugged terrain.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Tidally Locked Rotation: Mercury - A Planet Stuck in a Celestial Synchronization Dance!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Discover the mesmerizing effect of tidal locking on Mercury, as the planet\'s rotation is synchronized with its orbit around the Sun, causing it to experience three rotations on its axis for every two orbits around the Sun, creating a unique celestial dance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":15,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/mercury2-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-15\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Shrinking Planet: Mercury - A World Undergoing Remarkable Contraction!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Witness the evidence of Mercury\'s shrinking size over billions of years, as its iron core cools and solidifies, causing the planet\'s surface to contract and creating vast cliffs and scarps that serve as a testament to its geological transformation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Insane Facts About Mercury','Mercury','inherit','closed','closed','','12-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:32:54','2023-05-16 21:32:54','',12,'https://unifacts.local/?p=119',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (121,1,'2023-05-16 21:35:48','2023-05-16 21:35:48','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/sun-1024x978.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Unleashing Stellar Fury: The Sun\'s Unmatched Nuclear Power</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Sun is a staggering nuclear fusion reactor, converting about 600 million tons of hydrogen into helium every second!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Solar Spectacular: The Sun\'s Explosive Dance of Fire and Light</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Sun emits energy in the form of light and heat, but it also produces captivating phenomena like solar flares and coronal mass ejections.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":9,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/sun1-1024x642.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-9\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Cosmic Colossus: The Sun\'s Jaw-Dropping Size Compared to Our Tiny Planet</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Sun is enormous, with a diameter of about 1.4 million kilometers (870,000 miles), making it about 109 times larger than Earth.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Unveiling the Fiery Heart: Exploring the Sun\'s Mysterious and Intense Core</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Deep within the Sun lies its core, a scorching-hot region where temperatures reach millions of degrees Celsius, fueling the Sun\'s immense energy output.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":10,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://unifacts.local/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/sun2-1024x682.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-10\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Sunlight Time Warp: Peering Into the Past With Every Glimpse of the Sun</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It takes about 8 minutes and 20 seconds for sunlight to reach Earth, meaning we see the Sun as it was over 8 minutes ago.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','5 Crazy Facts About the Sun','The Sun','inherit','closed','closed','','6-revision-v1','','','2023-05-16 21:35:48','2023-05-16 21:35:48','',6,'https://unifacts.local/?p=121',0,'revision','',0);
